<section id="app.shortcuts">
  <title id="app.shortcuts.title">OmegaT shortcuts</title>

  <section id="app.shortcuts.description">
    <title id="app.shortcuts.description.title">Description</title>

    <para>OmegaT generally does not use buttons to give you access to its
    functions. The functions are available from the menus and most of them have
    been assigned default shortcuts.</para>

	<para>You will only need a few minutes of working with OmegaT to remember
	the most frequent shortcuts, and you will always be able to learn new
	shortcuts from the menus.</para>

    <para>Almost all of OmegaT’s shortcuts are customizable. See <link
    endterm="app.shortcuts.customization.title"
    linkend="app.shortcuts.customization"/> for details.</para>

    <para>OmegaT runs on any platform that runs a Java Runtime Environment
    (Windows, macOS, Linux being the most mainstream). The modifier keys that
    compose the shortcuts vary slightly depending on the platform. To make
    reading easier we have adopted the following presentation for modifier keys:
	<table id="shortcut.description">
      <title id="shortcut.description.title">Modifier key description</title>

      <tgroup cols="3">
        <thead>
          <row>
            <entry>Linux/Windows</entry>
            <entry>Key description</entry>
            <entry>macOS</entry>
          </row>
        </thead>

        <tbody>
          <row>
            <entry><keycap>Shift</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>S</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>shift</keycap> or <keycap>⇧</keycap></entry>
          </row>

          <row>
            <entry><keycap>Control</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>C</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>command</keycap> or <keycap>⌘</keycap></entry>
          </row>

          <row>
            <entry><keycap>Alt</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>A</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>alt / option</keycap> or
            <keycap>⌥</keycap></entry>
          </row>

          <row>
            <entry/>
            <entry><keycap>Ctrl</keycap></entry>
            <entry><keycap>control</keycap> or <keycap>⌃</keycap></entry>
          </row>
        </tbody>
      </tgroup>
      </table></para>
      
      <para>We can thus use only the <emphasis role="bold">Key description</emphasis> codes above to avoid repeating multiple notations.</para>

          <example id="example.avoid.repeating.multiple.notations"><title id="example.avoid.repeating.multiple.notations.title">How we avoid repeating multiple notations:</title>
		<para>On Windows and Linux:
		  <keycombo><keycap>Control</keycap><keycap>Shift</keycap><keycap>N</keycap></keycombo>
		</para>
		<para>On macOS:
		  <keycombo><keycap>Shift</keycap><keycap>Command</keycap><keycap>N</keycap></keycombo>
		</para>
  		<para>In this manual:
		  <keycombo><keycap>C</keycap><keycap>S</keycap><keycap>N</keycap></keycombo>
		</para>
		</example>
  </section>

  <section id="app.shortcuts.customization">
    <title id="app.shortcuts.customization.title">Customization</title>

	<para>OmegaT assigns shortcuts to most functions available in the menus and
	to a number of functions in the Editor window. Most of these functions can
	be assigned new shortcuts.</para>
    <para>You can change or add a shortcut by putting a shortcut definition
    file in your OmegaT configuration folder. See <link
    endterm="configuration.folder.title" linkend="configuration.folder"/> for
    details.</para>

    <para>There are 2 shortcut definition files.</para>
	<variablelist>
	  <varlistentry><term id="MainMenuShortcuts.properties">MainMenuShortcuts.properties</term>
	  <listitem><para>The shortcut definition file for the menus and a few other items.</para></listitem></varlistentry>
	  <varlistentry><term id="EditorShortcuts.properties">EditorShortcuts.properties</term>
	  <listitem><para>The shortcut definition file for the editor.</para></listitem></varlistentry>
	</variablelist>

    <para>Once a shortcut definition file is modified, OmegaT must be relaunched
    to take the new shortcuts into account.</para>

    <note>
      <para>You can copy the default OmegaT shortcut files from the OmegaT
      development site on Sourceforge to your configuration folder and modify
      them to suit your needs:</para>

	  <variablelist>
		<varlistentry><term>Windows and Linux default shortcuts</term>
		<listitem>
		  <itemizedlist>
			<listitem>
			  <para><ulink
						url="https://sourceforge.net/p/omegat/svn/HEAD/tree/trunk/src/org/omegat/gui/main/MainMenuShortcuts.properties">MainMenuShortcuts.properties</ulink></para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
			  <para><ulink
						url="https://sourceforge.net/p/omegat/svn/HEAD/tree/trunk/src/org/omegat/gui/main/EditorShortcuts.properties">EditorShortcuts.properties</ulink></para>
			</listitem>
		  </itemizedlist>
		</listitem>
		</varlistentry>
		<varlistentry><term>macOS default shortcuts</term>
		<listitem>
		  <itemizedlist>
			<listitem>
			  <para><ulink
						url="https://sourceforge.net/p/omegat/svn/HEAD/tree/trunk/src/org/omegat/gui/main/MainMenuShortcuts.mac.properties">MainMenuShortcuts.mac.properties</ulink></para>
			</listitem>
			<listitem>
			  <para><ulink
						url="https://sourceforge.net/p/omegat/svn/HEAD/tree/trunk/src/org/omegat/gui/main/EditorShortcuts.mac.properties">EditorShortcuts.mac.properties</ulink></para>
			</listitem>
		  </itemizedlist>
		</listitem>
		</varlistentry>
	  </variablelist>
	  <para>The macOS files must be renamed <link linkend="MainMenuShortcuts.properties" endterm="MainMenuShortcuts.properties"/> and <link linkend="EditorShortcuts.properties" endterm="EditorShortcuts.properties"/> to be taken into account by OmegaT.</para>
    </note>
  </section>

  <section id="app.shortcuts.syntax">
    <title id="app.shortcuts.syntax.title">Syntax</title>

    <para>Empty lines are accepted and comment lines should start with
    <code>//</code>. Anything after the <code>//</code> will be
    ignored.</para>

    <para>The shortcut definition syntax is the following:</para>

    <para><code>function code=shortcut</code></para>

    <para><code>function code</code> is a code taken from the tables
    below.</para>

    <para><code>shortcut</code> is a combination of pressed keys
    specified by the user.</para>

    <para><code>shortcut</code> must be of the following form: <itemizedlist>
    <listitem>
      <para>0 or more <code>modifier</code></para>
    </listitem>

    <listitem>
      <para>followed by 0 or 1 <code>event</code></para>
    </listitem>

    <listitem>
      <para>followed by 1 <code>key</code></para>
    </listitem>
    </itemizedlist> where:</para>

    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para><code>modifier</code> can be:
        <emphasis>shift</emphasis>, <emphasis>control</emphasis>,
        <emphasis>ctrl</emphasis>, <emphasis>meta</emphasis>,
        <emphasis>alt</emphasis>, <emphasis>altGraph</emphasis></para>

        <note>
          <para><emphasis>meta</emphasis> is used to describe
          <emphasis>command</emphasis> on macOS.</para>
        </note>
      </listitem>

      <listitem>
        <para><code>event</code> can be: <emphasis>typed</emphasis>,
        <emphasis>pressed</emphasis>, <emphasis>released</emphasis></para>
      </listitem>

      <listitem>
        <para>and <code>key</code> can be any key available on your
        keyboard.</para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

    <example id="example.shortcut.modification">
      <title id="example.shortcut.modification.title"><guilabel>Open Project</guilabel> shortcut modification</title>

      <para>The default shortcut for <guilabel>Open Project</guilabel> is
      defined this way:</para>

      <para><code>projectOpenMenuItem=ctrl O</code></para>

      <para>or, on macOS</para>

      <para><code>projectOpenMenuItem=meta O</code>.</para>

      <para>If you want to add <keycap>Shift</keycap> to the definition,
      modify the <filename>MainMenuShortcuts.properties</filename> as
      follows:</para>

      <para><code>projectOpenMenuItem=shift ctrl O</code>.</para>

      <para>or, on macOS:</para>

      <para><code>projectOpenMenuItem=shift meta O</code>.</para>
    </example>

    <para>After the modifications, save the file and relaunch OmegaT. Your new
    shortcuts should now appear next to the menu items you have modified. If
    they do not conflict with system shortcuts, they should be available from
    within OmegaT.</para>

    <para>The following sections give the function codes and their
    associated shortcuts default definitions.</para>
  </section>

